{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":284701,"duration_api_ms":284626,"num_turns":31,"result":"","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"44753998-9509-43dc-a10a-7f4a529bfdf8","total_cost_usd":1.20830575,"usage":{"input_tokens":24,"cache_creation_input_tokens":55579,"cache_read_input_tokens":1112934,"output_tokens":12174,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":55579,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-opus-4-6":{"inputTokens":24,"outputTokens":12174,"cacheReadInputTokens":1112934,"cacheCreationInputTokens":55579,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":1.20830575,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":64000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"summary":"Reviewed changes across retry_policy.rs, process_backend.rs, tmux.rs, and retry_policy_test.rs. The implementation is solid: retry limits are correctly increased (TransportFailure→5, SchemaValidation→3, Timeout→3), BinaryNotFound is properly classified as terminal, confirm_teardown replaces fire-and-forget reaping in the timeout path, jitter is added to exponential backoff, and the tmux adapter now has a fallback kill path when cancel() fails during timeout. The core logic is correct and well-commented. Two substantive gaps remain: (1) the acceptance criteria require \"new tests cover timeout enforcement and retry backoff\" but no new tests were added — only one existing test was adapted, and (2) the spawn ENOENT guard has a subtle path-resolution issue with bare binary names.","amendments":[{"body":"Add test coverage for timeout enforcement and jitter as required by acceptance criteria. Specifically: (a) a test for `confirm_teardown` verifying that a killed process returns `teardown_confirmed=true` and a process that resists kill returns false; (b) a test for the unclean-timeout → TransportFailure mapping in the process backend timeout path; (c) a test verifying that jitter-enabled backoff produces values within the documented ±25% range (i.e., `backoff_for_attempt(1)` on the default policy returns a Duration in `[3.75s, 6.25s)`). The diff adds zero new test functions despite the acceptance criteria explicitly stating 'new tests cover timeout enforcement and retry backoff'.","rationale":"The acceptance criteria explicitly require 'new tests cover timeout enforcement and retry backoff'. Only one existing test line was changed (adding with_no_jitter). No new tests exist for confirm_teardown, the unclean-timeout → TransportFailure mapping, the tmux fallback kill path, or jitter bounds. This leaves the most complex new code paths (async kill + wait with grace period, failure class selection based on teardown outcome) completely untested."},{"body":"In process_backend.rs ~line 1003, the `!binary.exists()` guard on the spawn ENOENT handler is unreliable when `binary` is a bare name (e.g., `PathBuf(\"claude\")`) because `Path::exists()` resolves relative to CWD, not PATH. When no explicit search paths are configured, `resolve_binary` returns the bare name for OS PATH lookup. If spawn returns ENOENT because the working directory or script interpreter is missing (not the binary itself), and `./claude` also doesn't exist in CWD, the error is misclassified as `BinaryNotFound` (terminal) instead of `TransportFailure` (retryable). Fix: use `which::which()` or replicate PATH resolution before the `exists()` check, or guard with `self.search_paths.is_some()` so the check only applies when the binary path is known to be absolute.","rationale":"The comment on the guard correctly identifies that spawn ENOENT can mean missing binary, missing working directory, or missing script interpreter. But `binary.exists()` on a bare name checks CWD, not the resolved PATH location. In the default no-search-paths config, this check is effectively 'does ./claude exist in CWD?' which almost always returns false, causing all spawn ENOENT errors to be classified as BinaryNotFound regardless of root cause. While the most common case (binary truly missing) happens to get the right answer, the guard doesn't actually distinguish the cases it claims to."}]},"fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"bf51befe-9275-49c0-8310-b4a0b0425118"}
